---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "How do I implement right to erasure in a database?",
    answer: "The simplest approach is soft deletion with anonymization rather than hard deletion — this preserves referential integrity and audit logs while removing personal data. When a user requests erasure: set a deleted_at timestamp, replace all PII fields (name, email, phone, address) with null or a placeholder like '[deleted]', remove from backup-scoped tables. For hard deletion, you must also purge the user from all backups within a reasonable timeframe, which is operationally complex. Consider a 'right to erasure job' table that tracks what needs to be purged from backup snapshots as they rotate. Document your erasure procedure as it will be required evidence in a DPA or audit."
  },
  {
    question: "What data requires explicit consent vs legitimate interest?",
    answer: "Explicit consent is required for: marketing emails and newsletters, tracking cookies and behavioral advertising, sensitive personal data (health, biometric, racial/ethnic origin, political opinions), and processing that users would not reasonably expect. Legitimate interest can justify: fraud prevention, security monitoring, service improvement analytics, B2B prospecting (with opt-out), and processing necessary for contract performance. The key test for legitimate interest is the 'balancing test': does your interest override the data subject's rights? Always document your lawful basis decision in a Records of Processing Activities (ROPA) document."
  },
  {
    question: "What is a Data Processing Agreement and when is it required?",
    answer: "A Data Processing Agreement (DPA) is a contract required under GDPR Article 28 whenever you share personal data with a third-party processor — any vendor that processes data on your behalf. This includes cloud providers (AWS, GCP), analytics platforms (Mixpanel, Segment), email services (SendGrid, Mailchimp), support tools (Intercom, Zendesk), and CRM systems. The DPA must specify the categories of data, processing purposes, security measures, sub-processor restrictions, and data subject rights procedures. Most major vendors provide a standard DPA — you typically accept it in their settings or compliance portal."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I handle data breach notification under GDPR?",
    answer: "GDPR Article 33 requires notifying your supervisory authority (the DPA in your EU country) within 72 hours of discovering a breach that risks the rights and freedoms of natural persons. The notification must include: nature of the breach, categories and number of affected individuals, likely consequences, and measures taken/proposed. If the breach is high-risk to individuals (e.g., passwords, financial data, health data), you must also directly notify affected users without undue delay (Article 34). Build an incident response runbook with pre-drafted notification templates, contact info for your DPA, and a decision tree for assessing breach risk level."
  },
  {
    question: "What is a DPIA and when is it required?",
    answer: "A Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA) is required before starting processing that is 'likely to result in a high risk' to individuals — specifically: systematic profiling, large-scale processing of sensitive data, systematic monitoring of public areas, combining datasets that could identify individuals, processing data about vulnerable subjects, using new technologies, automated decision-making with legal effects. A DPIA documents: description of the processing, necessity and proportionality assessment, risk to data subjects, and measures to mitigate those risks. Your DPA may publish a list of processing types that always require a DPIA. Keep DPIAs on file as regulators may request them."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the difference between a GDPR controller and processor?",
    answer: "A controller determines the purposes and means of processing — why and how personal data is processed. A processor acts on behalf of the controller following their instructions. For example, if you run a SaaS HR platform: your customer (the company) is the controller of employee data; you (the SaaS vendor) are the processor. Controllers bear primary GDPR responsibility and must have a DPA with each processor. Processors must only process data per controller instructions and must notify controllers of breaches. You can be both: as a controller for your own users' data (accounts, billing) and a processor for data your customers upload to your platform."
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="GDPR Developer Guide: Technical Requirements & Implementation Checklist"
  description="GDPR technical requirements for developers: lawful basis, data minimization, right to erasure API, consent management, data breach notification, DPIAs, and privacy by design."
  tool="GDPR, data privacy, right to erasure, consent management, DPIA, privacy by design, data breach"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "GDPR Developer Guide: Technical Requirements & Implementation Checklist",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/gdpr-developer-guide",
    "description": "GDPR technical requirements for developers: lawful basis, data minimization, right to erasure API, consent management, data breach notification, DPIAs, and privacy by design.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">GDPR Developer Guide: Technical Requirements & Implementation Checklist</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">GDPR compliance is not just a legal checkbox — it requires specific technical implementations in your API design, database schema, and data pipeline. This guide focuses on what developers actually need to build: erasure endpoints, consent tracking, breach notification procedures, and privacy-by-design patterns.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Right to erasure implementation</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Consent management patterns</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Data breach 72-hour rule</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> DPIA checklist</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> GDPR vs CCPA vs LGPD</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">GDPR Key Principles for Developers</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">GDPR is built on six processing principles that should shape your technical design decisions:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>Lawfulness, fairness, transparency</strong> — Have a documented lawful basis; tell users what you collect</li>
    <li><strong>Purpose limitation</strong> — Collect data for a specific purpose; don't repurpose it</li>
    <li><strong>Data minimization</strong> — Only collect what you need; avoid "just in case" fields</li>
    <li><strong>Accuracy</strong> — Keep data up to date; provide user correction mechanisms</li>
    <li><strong>Storage limitation</strong> — Delete data when no longer needed; implement retention policies</li>
    <li><strong>Integrity and confidentiality</strong> — Encrypt in transit and at rest; access controls</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Lawful Basis for Processing</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Lawful Basis</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">When to Use</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">User Right to Object?</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Consent</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Marketing, tracking cookies, newsletters</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes, withdraw anytime</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Contract</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Data needed to deliver the service</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">No (needed for service)</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Legal obligation</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Tax records, KYC/AML</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">No</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Legitimate interests</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Fraud prevention, security, analytics</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes (balancing test required)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">Vital interests</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Life-threatening emergencies</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Rarely applicable</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Right to Erasure: Soft Delete Pattern</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code>-- Database schema for privacy-safe soft deletion
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN deleted_at TIMESTAMP;
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN erasure_requested_at TIMESTAMP;

-- Erasure procedure: anonymize PII fields
UPDATE users SET
  email = CONCAT('deleted-', id, '@erased.invalid'),
  name = '[Deleted User]',
  phone = NULL,
  address = NULL,
  date_of_birth = NULL,
  ip_address = NULL,
  deleted_at = NOW(),
  erasure_requested_at = NOW()
WHERE id = $1;</code></pre>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code>// Express route: DELETE /api/users/me (authenticated)
app.delete('/api/users/me', authenticate, async (req, res) =&gt; &#123;
  const userId = req.user.id;

  // 1. Queue erasure job (async — respects 30-day backup rotation)
  await db.erasureQueue.create(&#123;
    userId,
    requestedAt: new Date(),
    status: 'pending',
  &#125;);

  // 2. Immediately anonymize active record
  await db.users.anonymize(userId);

  // 3. Revoke active sessions
  await db.sessions.deleteByUserId(userId);

  // 4. Notify downstream services (analytics, CRM)
  await erasureEvent.emit('user.erased', &#123; userId &#125;);

  res.json(&#123; message: 'Your data has been scheduled for deletion.' &#125;);
&#125;);</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Data Minimization in API Design</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code>// Bad: returning all user fields including PII not needed by client
app.get('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) =&gt; &#123;
  const user = await db.users.findById(req.params.id);
  res.json(user); // Leaks DOB, phone, full address
&#125;);

// Good: return only fields the client actually needs
app.get('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) =&gt; &#123;
  const user = await db.users.findById(req.params.id, &#123;
    select: ['id', 'displayName', 'avatarUrl', 'createdAt'],
  &#125;);
  res.json(user);
&#125;);

// Good: use GraphQL field selection to prevent over-fetching
// clients can only request explicitly allowed fields</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Consent Management (CMP Integration)</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code">// Store consent with audit trail
const consentRecord = &#123;
  userId: user.id,
  consentVersion: '2024-01-15',  // tie to your privacy policy version
  purposes: &#123;
    analytics: true,
    marketing: false,
    functional: true,
  &#125;,
  collectedAt: new Date(),
  ipAddress: req.ip,  // evidence of consent timing
  userAgent: req.headers['user-agent'],
&#125;;

// Never rely on a boolean — store the full consent record
await db.consentLog.create(consentRecord);

// Check consent before sending marketing
async function canSendMarketing(userId) &#123;
  const latest = await db.consentLog.findLatest(userId);
  return latest?.purposes?.marketing === true;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Data Breach Notification: 72-Hour Rule</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">When a breach is discovered, the clock starts immediately. Build a runbook with these steps:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-1">
    <li><strong>0-4 hours</strong>: Contain breach (revoke compromised tokens, block attacker IP, isolate affected systems)</li>
    <li><strong>4-24 hours</strong>: Assess scope (what data, how many users, what type of data)</li>
    <li><strong>24-48 hours</strong>: Draft supervisory authority notification with known facts; engage DPO</li>
    <li><strong>48-72 hours</strong>: File notification with your lead supervisory authority (even if incomplete — update later)</li>
    <li><strong>If high-risk</strong>: Also notify affected users directly within same window</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">DPIA Checklist</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">A DPIA is required when your processing is "high risk." Check if your feature requires one:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-1">
    <li>Systematic profiling or automated decision-making with legal/significant effects</li>
    <li>Large-scale processing of special category data (health, biometric, financial)</li>
    <li>Systematic monitoring of publicly accessible areas</li>
    <li>Combining datasets from different sources to identify individuals</li>
    <li>Processing data of vulnerable subjects (children, patients)</li>
    <li>Using new technologies (AI models, biometric matching)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">GDPR vs CCPA vs LGPD</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Feature</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">GDPR (EU)</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">CCPA (California)</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">LGPD (Brazil)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Consent required</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes (many cases)</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Opt-out model</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes (similar to GDPR)</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Right to erasure</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Article 17 (strong)</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes (limited)</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Article 18</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Max fine</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">€20M or 4% global revenue</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">$7,500 per intentional violation</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">2% Brazil revenue</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">Breach notification</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">72 hours to DPA</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Expedient notice</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Reasonable timeframe</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <ToolPageCta />
  <FaqSection faqs={faq} />
</BaseLayout>
